dant of <i>Cuinneagán</i>’, a personal name from a double diminutive of the Old Irish personal name <i>Conn</i> meaning ‘leader, chief’. This name is also adopted for <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Malcolm de Cunynghame was born in 1040, in Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Okant Friskin DeCunningham, was 41 and his mother, Mrs Okant Friskin DeCunninghame, was 41. He married Agnes Laverock in 1080, in Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1096, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1040–about 1096":"1040–umbes 1096","1040–1096":"1040–1096","1044–Female":"1044–Surnud","1085–1140":"1085–1140","1000–1040":"1000–1040","1000–Female":"1000–Surnud",